            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this character counter works</h2>
              <p>
                This character counter updates in real time as you type or paste
                text. It is designed for writers, developers, marketers,
                students, and anyone who needs precise length limits for tweets,
                SMS messages, SEO snippets, UI copy, or database fields.
              </p>
              <p>
                Unlike basic counters, this tool shows multiple metrics side by
                side: characters (with and without spaces), words, sentences,
                paragraphs, lines, spaces, digits, letters, punctuation, emojis,
                bytes, and estimated reading time.
              </p>

              <h3>What each metric means</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Characters (with spaces)</strong> – Every visible
                  character plus spaces, tabs, and line breaks. This is the most
                  common limit for social media and SEO.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Characters (no spaces)</strong> – All characters
                  except whitespace. Useful when a platform ignores spaces in
                  its limit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Words</strong> – Groups of non‑whitespace characters
                  separated by spaces, line breaks, or punctuation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sentences</strong> – Segments ending in
                  <code>.</code>, <code>!</code>, or <code>?</code> (with some
                  basic handling of multiple punctuation marks).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Paragraphs</strong> – Blocks of text separated by one
                  or more blank lines.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lines</strong> – Lines separated by line breaks
                  (<code>\n</code>).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Spaces</strong> – Space characters only (not tabs or
                  line breaks).
                </li>
                <li><strong>Digits</strong> – Characters <code>0–9</code>.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Letters</strong> – Alphabetic characters (A–Z, a–z and
                  most Unicode letters).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Punctuation</strong> – Common punctuation marks such
                  as <code>.,;:!?'"-</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Emoji &amp; symbols</strong> – Non‑alphanumeric
                  characters that are not counted as basic punctuation,
                  including many emojis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bytes (UTF‑8)</strong> – The size of your text in
                  bytes when encoded as UTF‑8, which is how most modern systems
                  store text.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Reading time</strong> – An estimate based on an
                  average reading speed of about 200 words per minute.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Character limits and remaining characters</h3>
              <p>
                Use the quick limit buttons (Twitter, SMS, meta description, SEO
                title) or set a custom limit. The tool will:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Show how many characters you have left.</li>
                <li>Turn the remaining count red when you exceed the limit.</li>
                <li>
                  Display a short status message (e.g., “12 characters over the
                  limit”).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                When no limit is active, the remaining field shows
                <strong>∞</strong> and no warning is displayed.
              </p>

              <h3>Why byte count matters (UTF‑8)</h3>
              <p>
                Many systems limit text by <em>bytes</em> instead of characters.
                In UTF‑8 encoding:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Most basic Latin characters (A–Z, a–z, digits, common
                  punctuation) use <strong>1 byte</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Accented characters and many non‑Latin scripts use
                  <strong>2–3 bytes</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>Most emojis use <strong>4 bytes</strong>.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This means two strings with the same character count can have
                very different byte sizes. If you are working with database
                column limits (e.g., <code>VARCHAR(160)</code>), APIs, or SMS
                gateways, always check the byte count as well.
              </p>

